(Mr. Froom groans)

298
00:16:51,740 --> 00:16:52,690
(Mr. Froom groans)
(Benderfax gasps)

299
00:16:52,690 --> 00:16:53,650
(Benderfax gasps)
(Mr. Froom groans)

300
00:16:55,700 --> 00:16:59,660
(distant sleepy piano)

301
00:17:01,540 --> 00:17:04,500
- Ah...Froom's room, I presume.

302
00:17:04,500 --> 00:17:06,540
- Hm...Mr. Froom...

303
00:17:06,880 --> 00:17:08,710
He used to decorate his door
to help him remember...

304
00:17:08,710 --> 00:17:10,130
which room was his.

305
00:17:10,130 --> 00:17:13,590
- Hm...So I take it Mr. Froom is...oh!
Checked out...

306
00:17:13,610 --> 00:17:17,140
- Yeah, you could say that...
He died in his sleep last night.

307
00:17:17,150 --> 00:17:18,100
- I'm sorry...

308
00:17:18,100 --> 00:17:19,420
What was the cause of death?

309
00:17:19,420 --> 00:17:23,100
- I think Nurse Clench said
it was a cerebral aneurism.

310
00:17:23,100 --> 00:17:25,770
- Hm...Well how did they
determine that so quickly?

311
00:17:25,770 --> 00:17:28,990
- Um...Dr. Benderfax examined him himself.

312
00:17:28,990 --> 00:17:30,220
- Oh, really?

313
00:17:30,220 --> 00:17:31,050
- Yeah...

314
00:17:31,050 --> 00:17:33,770
There's a new patient
in Mr. Froom's room now...

315
00:17:33,770 --> 00:17:35,970
A 70 year old woman named Wilma Beagle...

316
00:17:35,970 --> 00:17:38,200
Apparently, she was homeless...

317
00:17:38,200 --> 00:17:41,410
She was brought here
after suffering a minor stroke...

318
00:17:41,410 --> 00:17:45,000
She's improving, but for now
she's still unable to speak...

319
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:46,960
and has no feeling in her left hand.

320
00:17:55,340 --> 00:17:57,180
- Poor woman.

321
00:18:01,260 --> 00:18:04,640
(dramatic upbeat music)

322
00:18:39,350 --> 00:18:40,300
- Oh!

323
00:18:44,810 --> 00:18:46,520
Hello?

324
00:18:47,300 --> 00:18:48,350
Hm...

325
00:18:55,230 --> 00:18:58,070
(distant sleepy piano)

326
00:18:58,530 --> 00:19:08,200
(Andrew whistles)

327
00:19:19,380 --> 00:19:20,550
- Hi Wilma.

328
00:19:21,890 --> 00:19:24,600
What do you have there?

329
00:19:35,570 --> 00:19:38,420
(dramatic upbeat music)

330
00:19:43,320 --> 00:19:45,700
(phone rings)

331
00:19:47,160 --> 00:19:48,180
- Hello.

332
00:19:48,830 --> 00:19:50,410
- Hi, Carmen?

333
00:19:50,410 --> 00:19:52,500
Hi, it's Andrew March, over at the Institute.

334
00:19:52,870 --> 00:19:55,250
- Oh, hi Andrew...What a surprise.

335
00:19:55,500 --> 00:19:57,460
- I hope you don't mind
me calling you like this...

336
00:19:57,460 --> 00:19:59,550
I had your number in my office Rolodex.

337
00:19:59,550 --> 00:20:01,330
- [Carmen] Oh no, not at all...

338
00:20:01,330 --> 00:20:02,840
What can I do for you?

339
00:20:04,840 --> 00:20:05,970
Really?

340
00:20:05,970 --> 00:20:07,430
What did it say?

341
00:20:07,850 --> 00:20:09,100
- I'm not quite sure...

342
00:20:09,100 --> 00:20:11,270
but I'd like you take a look at it...

343
00:20:11,270 --> 00:20:12,890
Could I interest you in a bite to eat?

344
00:20:13,080 --> 00:20:14,480
- Oh, sounds fine...

345
00:20:14,480 --> 00:20:16,910
Just give me a couple
minutes to change, okay?

346
00:20:18,150 --> 00:20:19,610
- I can pick you up if you'd like...

347
00:20:19,610 --> 00:20:20,400
Um...

348
00:20:20,400 --> 00:20:22,610
Do you still live at 3967 Normal Street?

349
00:20:24,070 --> 00:20:25,030
- So...

350
00:20:25,030 --> 00:20:26,780
You know my address, too...

351
00:20:26,780 --> 00:20:26,790
(Farance gasps)
You know my address, too...

352
00:20:26,790 --> 00:20:27,780
(Farance gasps)

353
00:20:27,780 --> 00:20:29,840
Very interesting.
(Farance gasps)

354
00:20:29,840 --> 00:20:32,730
So, if you ever wanted to send me something...

355
00:20:34,710 --> 00:20:37,290
- I guess I'd be prepared, wouldn't I?

356
00:20:38,370 --> 00:20:39,460
How much time will you need?

357
00:20:40,020 --> 00:20:41,710
- Just give me 20 minutes, okay?

358
00:20:41,710 --> 00:20:41,720
(Farance gasps)
- Just give me 20 minutes, okay?

359
00:20:41,720 --> 00:20:44,510
(Farance gasps)

360
00:20:44,510 --> 00:20:46,390
Sounds great...

361
00:20:46,390 --> 00:20:47,320
Bye Andrew.

362
00:20:47,320 --> 00:20:50,810
(Farance gasps)

363
00:20:53,060 --> 00:20:54,350
(grunts)

364
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:05,090
(romantic music in cafe)
♪ Now that love is won ♪

365
00:21:05,090 --> 00:21:07,910
(Carmen and Andrew laugh)
♪ Life has just begun ♪

366
00:21:08,200 --> 00:21:09,740
- Thanks.

367
00:21:10,790 --> 00:21:13,160
- So, what about this note
you said Wilma wrote?

368
00:21:13,160 --> 00:21:14,310
- Oh...

369
00:21:14,310 --> 00:21:15,650
I have it right here....

370
00:21:17,130 --> 00:21:17,710
I don't know...

371
00:21:17,710 --> 00:21:20,300
It's probably just a bunch of scribbles.

372
00:21:20,550 --> 00:21:21,460
- Hm...

373
00:21:21,570 --> 00:21:23,260
In...

374
00:21:23,260 --> 00:21:24,720
Innocent?

375
00:21:26,510 --> 00:21:27,890
- Do you think she was trying to say...

376
00:21:27,890 --> 00:21:29,600
she was an innocent victim?

377
00:21:30,100 --> 00:21:31,700
- Well, she was attacked...

378
00:21:31,700 --> 00:21:33,640
She's probably still very frightened.

379
00:21:35,310 --> 00:21:38,230
- It just makes me sick
thinking of some creep...

380
00:21:38,230 --> 00:21:40,950
beating up on that frail old woman...

381
00:21:40,950 --> 00:21:43,820
I mean, what kind of world
are we living in anyway?

382
00:21:43,820 --> 00:21:47,780
- Andrew, do you always get so
emotional over your patients?

383
00:21:49,490 --> 00:21:51,000
- I'm sorry...

384
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:53,410
It's hard to be detached, sometimes.

385
00:21:53,410 --> 00:21:55,660
- Yeah, like with Mr. Froom...

386
00:21:55,660 --> 00:21:57,640
He was admitted to the Institute...

387
00:21:57,640 --> 00:21:59,430
the day I started working there.

388
00:21:59,430 --> 00:22:01,580
He was a sweet old man...

389
00:22:01,580 --> 00:22:03,590
I guess that's why I keep
putting off taking down...

390
00:22:03,590 --> 00:22:05,510
all those names from his door.

391
00:22:05,760 --> 00:22:08,890
- Sounds like we're both a bit
sentimental, Carmen.

392
00:22:09,510 --> 00:22:11,460
- I won't tell anybody, if you don't.

393
00:22:11,460 --> 00:22:14,810
(Carmen and Andrew laugh)

394
00:22:17,280 --> 00:22:20,330
(romantic music)

395
00:22:20,330 --> 00:22:22,440
- [Andrew] I had a really nice time tonight.

396
00:22:23,150 --> 00:22:24,710
- So did I...

397
00:22:24,820 --> 00:22:26,990
By the way...thanks for the flowers.

398
00:22:28,360 --> 00:22:29,780
- Flowers?

399
00:22:29,780 --> 00:22:30,990
- Oh...

400
00:22:30,990 --> 00:22:33,330
What am I saying? It must be getting late...

401
00:22:33,330 --> 00:22:36,540
I meant, thank you for
inviting me out tonight.

402
00:22:37,500 --> 00:22:39,330
- Well, it was my pleasure...

403
00:22:39,420 --> 00:22:40,460
Oh and next time...

404
00:22:40,790 --> 00:22:42,960
I'm bringing flowers.

405
00:22:42,960 --> 00:22:44,000
- Oh, I didn't mean...

406
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:47,130
that I thought that you should--
-Oh, no, no, no, no. Of course not.

407
00:22:49,320 --> 00:22:50,640
- Goodnight, Andrew.

408
00:22:51,890 --> 00:22:53,550
- Goodnight, Carmen.

409
00:23:04,020 --> 00:23:07,280
(distant sleepy piano)

410
00:23:15,090 --> 00:23:16,510
- Hello, young man...

411
00:23:16,510 --> 00:23:18,160
Joe, isn't it?

412
00:23:18,160 --> 00:23:19,350
- Farance, Ma'am.

413
00:23:19,350 --> 00:23:20,180
- Oh, yes...

414
00:23:20,180 --> 00:23:21,010
Farance...

415
00:23:21,010 --> 00:23:23,240
I hope you won't mind if I pay
you for the milk next time...

416
00:23:23,240 --> 00:23:27,090
My husband forgot to leave me
the money to pay you again...

417
00:23:27,090 --> 00:23:29,550
He's getting so forgetful these days.

418
00:23:29,550 --> 00:23:32,950
- It's no problem...
but it's only water, Mrs. Seawinner...

419
00:23:32,950 --> 00:23:34,810
Did ya sleep well last night?

420
00:23:34,810 --> 00:23:36,370
- Just like a log.

421
00:23:36,370 --> 00:23:37,410
- Glad to hear it...

422
00:23:37,410 --> 00:23:38,610
I'll see you later.

423
00:23:38,610 --> 00:23:40,280
- Thank you for the milk, Farance...

424
00:23:41,440 --> 00:23:43,370
Nice man, that Farance.

425
00:23:51,760 --> 00:23:53,570
- Well...

426
00:23:53,570 --> 00:23:55,160
This is it.

427
00:23:55,160 --> 00:23:56,990
- Have you read many endocrine panels?

428
00:23:56,990 --> 00:23:59,410
- A few...You?

429
00:23:59,410 --> 00:24:01,890
- Well, all the patients
get tested once a month.

430
00:24:01,890 --> 00:24:03,670
- How do they feel about blood tests?

431
00:24:03,670 --> 00:24:05,420
- I haven't had any complaints yet.

432
00:24:05,420 --> 00:24:07,960
- Well, you probably have
excellent bedside manner.

433
00:24:07,960 --> 00:24:11,160
(glasses clatter)

434
00:24:11,160 --> 00:24:12,840
- Oh, Farance...Have you met him yet?

435
00:24:12,850 --> 00:24:13,860
- No, I haven't.

436
00:24:13,860 --> 00:24:15,760
- Farance, can you come
over here for a minute?

437
00:24:15,760 --> 00:24:17,680
I'd like you to meet someone.

438
00:24:17,680 --> 00:24:19,930
- Yes, I'll be right there.

439
00:24:25,190 --> 00:24:27,150
- Farance...this is Dr. March.

440
00:24:27,150 --> 00:24:29,830
(spine-chilling music)

441
00:24:30,680 --> 00:24:32,800
- [Andrew] It's a pleasure to meet you, Farance.

442
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:34,620
- Oh, welcome to the Institute, Doctor.

443
00:24:34,620 --> 00:24:36,030
- [Andrew] Thanks, it's great to be here.

444
00:24:36,200 --> 00:24:38,780
- If you would excuse me...
I was just on the way to the head...

445
00:24:38,780 --> 00:24:39,490
- [Andrew] Huh?

446
00:24:39,490 --> 00:24:41,030
- I mean the lavatory.

447
00:24:42,120 --> 00:24:43,960
- Certainly...

448
00:24:46,850 --> 00:24:47,680
Is he--

449
00:24:47,680 --> 00:24:49,820
- Farance was once a
promising medical student...

450
00:24:49,820 --> 00:24:51,260
until he developed schizophrenia...

451
00:24:51,260 --> 00:24:52,820
and began having hallucinations.

452
00:24:52,820 --> 00:24:53,770
- Really?

453
00:24:53,770 --> 00:24:55,370
- Yeah...His condition's greatly improved...

454
00:24:55,370 --> 00:24:56,900
since he's been on medication...

455
00:24:56,900 --> 00:24:59,220
He's been living in the city
on his own for over a year...

456
00:24:59,220 --> 00:25:01,680
but he likes to keep
in contact with the Institute...

457
00:25:01,680 --> 00:25:03,470
delivering water to the patients...

458
00:25:03,470 --> 00:25:04,560
helping out in the kitchen.

459
00:25:04,560 --> 00:25:05,980
- I see.

460
00:25:05,980 --> 00:25:07,980
- Andrew, uh...
Could you excuse me for a minute?

461
00:25:07,980 --> 00:25:09,650
- Yeah, sure.

462
00:25:14,110 --> 00:25:16,490
(water splashing)
- Oh...

463
00:25:16,490 --> 00:25:20,790
(ominous music)

464
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:29,840
(distant piano)

465
00:25:29,920 --> 00:25:31,480
- Farance, wait a minute...

466
00:25:31,480 --> 00:25:31,880
Are you okay?

467
00:25:31,880 --> 00:25:34,510
- Me? Yes, I'm fine...

468
00:25:34,510 --> 00:25:35,310
What is it?

469
00:25:36,520 --> 00:25:38,620
- Somebody sent me flowers last night.

470
00:25:38,620 --> 00:25:39,890
- Yeah, really?

471
00:25:40,180 --> 00:25:41,720
- Yeah...There was a note attached...

472
00:25:41,720 --> 00:25:43,050
but it didn't say who they were from...

473
00:25:43,050 --> 00:25:44,560
I thought maybe you--

474
00:25:44,560 --> 00:25:45,580
- Me?

475
00:25:45,580 --> 00:25:46,410
No, it wasn't me...

476
00:25:46,410 --> 00:25:48,400
I had to work really late last night...

477
00:25:48,400 --> 00:25:49,610
It must have been somebody else.

478
00:25:50,020 --> 00:25:52,070
- I hope you're not lying to me, Farance.

479
00:25:52,560 --> 00:25:53,390
- No, honest...

480
00:25:53,690 --> 00:25:55,860
Maybe it was that new doctor, um...

481
00:25:55,860 --> 00:25:57,070
What's his name?

482
00:25:57,070 --> 00:25:57,820
- [Carmen] Dr. March?

483
00:25:57,820 --> 00:25:59,480
- Yes, maybe he sent 'em.

484
00:25:59,480 --> 00:26:01,490
- Why would you think that?

485
00:26:01,490 --> 00:26:03,040
- I don't know...It's just that...

486
00:26:03,040 --> 00:26:05,200
you an him seem to be getting on so well and--

487
00:26:05,210 --> 00:26:06,080
- [Carmen] Yeah, well...

488
00:26:06,080 --> 00:26:08,450
Dr. March said he didn't send them either.

489
00:26:08,450 --> 00:26:09,280
- Hm...

490
00:26:10,430 --> 00:26:12,550
Well, I'm sorry I can't help you, Carmen, but...

491
00:26:12,550 --> 00:26:14,030
I hope you do figure it out.

492
00:26:14,030 --> 00:26:15,520
- Yeah, sorry to bother you, Farance.

493
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:17,550
- Oh, no bother...See you later.

494
00:26:23,710 --> 00:26:26,600
- These accidents are happening
too often, Thomas...

495
00:26:26,600 --> 00:26:28,800
Mr. Froom had relatives, you know?

496
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:30,690
They're going to want to know
what happened to him.

497
00:26:30,690 --> 00:26:32,510
- It's all in the death certificate...

498
00:26:32,510 --> 00:26:36,180
A cerebral aneurism in his sleep...

499
00:26:36,180 --> 00:26:38,200
Why should they question it?

500
00:26:38,200 --> 00:26:40,570
They should be thrilled
the old bugger's dead!

501
00:26:40,570 --> 00:26:44,190
- I'm not asking you to stop
your experiments, Thomas...

502
00:26:44,190 --> 00:26:46,080
Just allow me to select the subjects...

503
00:26:46,080 --> 00:26:47,410
as I have from the beginning.

504
00:26:47,410 --> 00:26:48,620
- All right, Lavinia...

505
00:26:49,330 --> 00:26:52,130
but I have to have a
replacement subject by tonight...

506
00:26:52,130 --> 00:26:54,880
I'm in a critical stage
with my experiments...

507
00:26:54,880 --> 00:26:56,840
and I don't want any further delays.

508
00:26:56,960 --> 00:26:58,320
- [Clench] Your young doctor...

509
00:26:58,320 --> 00:27:00,460
is running endocrine panels today...

510
00:27:00,460 --> 00:27:02,660
We should get the results
by this afternoon.

511
00:27:03,430 --> 00:27:05,350
- Hi, Mrs. Seawinner...How are you?

512
00:27:05,350 --> 00:27:07,220
- Fine...Joe, isn't it?

513
00:27:07,750 --> 00:27:09,270
- No, Ma'am, it's Andrew.

514
00:27:09,270 --> 00:27:10,540
- Oh, yes, Andrew...

515
00:27:10,540 --> 00:27:11,650
You're new, aren't you?

516
00:27:11,650 --> 00:27:13,430
- Yeah, I just started here.

517
00:27:14,530 --> 00:27:18,410
(Mrs. Seawinner screams)

518
00:27:18,410 --> 00:27:19,260
Ah!

519
00:27:19,260 --> 00:27:20,830
Here's hold this on there...

520
00:27:20,830 --> 00:27:23,750
(Mrs. Seawinner gasps)

521
00:27:23,750 --> 00:27:25,130
Sorry, Mrs. Seawinner.

522
00:27:26,240 --> 00:27:28,160
(Mrs. Seawinner sniffles)

523
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:31,030
Hello, Larry...

524
00:27:31,910 --> 00:27:32,740
[Andrew] Uh...

525
00:27:34,420 --> 00:27:35,920
[Andrew] Uh...Larry?

526
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:37,960
[Andrew] Hi Fred, How you doing today?

527
00:27:37,960 --> 00:27:41,680
You know, I saw you making eyes
at Mrs. Smithers, in room 201...

528
00:27:41,680 --> 00:27:43,010
(Andrew laughs)

