00:27:45,930 --> 00:27:47,930
All right...You're all set.

530
00:27:47,930 --> 00:27:48,930
- Hm...

531
00:27:48,930 --> 00:27:51,230
What about that new admission...
the Jane Doe?

532
00:27:51,560 --> 00:27:53,650
- She appears to have suffered a stroke...

533
00:27:53,650 --> 00:27:57,010
She's mute, and there's some
paralysis in the left arm...

534
00:27:57,010 --> 00:28:00,570
I went through the old files
the military left in the basement...

535
00:28:00,570 --> 00:28:02,240
and I found her a good match...

536
00:28:02,240 --> 00:28:04,820
with an Army nurse named, Wilma Beagle...

537
00:28:04,820 --> 00:28:06,700
who died in 1945...

538
00:28:06,910 --> 00:28:09,700
I admitted our Jane Doe under that name.

539
00:28:09,700 --> 00:28:11,210
- Excellent...

540
00:28:11,210 --> 00:28:14,000
I'm anxious to see her adrenal output.

541
00:28:14,250 --> 00:28:16,640
- You'll have to wait for the test results...

542
00:28:16,640 --> 00:28:18,170
but I wouldn't get your hopes up...

543
00:28:18,170 --> 00:28:19,880
She's quite catatonic.

544
00:28:20,100 --> 00:28:21,170
- Hm...

545
00:28:21,170 --> 00:28:23,090
That may not matter...

546
00:28:23,090 --> 00:28:26,600
Get me those test results
as quickly as you can...

547
00:28:26,600 --> 00:28:30,220
I'm looking forward to meeting our Wilma.

548
00:28:30,730 --> 00:28:32,350
- [Andrew] Hi, Wilma...

549
00:28:34,650 --> 00:28:36,980
Wilma, can you hear me?

550
00:28:38,400 --> 00:28:40,940
What does this note say?

551
00:28:40,940 --> 00:28:43,820
Does that say innocent?

552
00:28:45,290 --> 00:28:48,080
- Maybe she can hear us...
but she's just unable to respond...

553
00:28:48,080 --> 00:28:49,990
See if she'll write something.

554
00:28:53,410 --> 00:28:56,540
- [Andrew] Here, Wilma...We'll take that...

555
00:28:56,540 --> 00:28:58,500
Here, hold this pen...

556
00:28:59,340 --> 00:29:02,300
Can you write something else for me?

557
00:29:02,320 --> 00:29:04,120
[Andrew] There you go...

558
00:29:16,230 --> 00:29:18,520
Thanks, Wilma.

559
00:29:22,070 --> 00:29:23,820
- Maybe we can try again tomorrow.

560
00:29:23,820 --> 00:29:26,280
- [Andrew] Yeah...
I guess she just needs more time.

561
00:29:32,880 --> 00:29:35,540
(dramatic upbeat music)

562
00:29:43,340 --> 00:29:45,720
(phone rings)

563
00:29:48,010 --> 00:29:49,360
Andrew March.

564
00:29:49,600 --> 00:29:51,350
- Have any plans tonight?

565
00:29:51,350 --> 00:29:52,220
- [Andrew] Carmen...

566
00:29:52,220 --> 00:29:53,720
I was just working on some, uh...

567
00:29:53,720 --> 00:29:56,200
dog illustrations for Dr. Benderfax...

568
00:29:56,200 --> 00:29:57,480
Did you have anything in mind?

569
00:29:57,480 --> 00:29:59,810
- Well, no...

570
00:29:59,810 --> 00:30:03,150
but there has been a lot of
activity in my ant farm, lately.

571
00:30:03,780 --> 00:30:05,650
- I see...

572
00:30:05,650 --> 00:30:06,860
Well, sure...

573
00:30:06,860 --> 00:30:10,370
Sure, I think I could stop by
and see your...ants.

574
00:30:10,700 --> 00:30:12,660
- What about your dog drawings?

575
00:30:12,660 --> 00:30:15,910
- [Andrew] Oh, I think I've put in
enough time on them for one night...

576
00:30:15,910 --> 00:30:17,580
Besides...

577
00:30:17,580 --> 00:30:19,420
I think the little fella
I've been working on...

578
00:30:19,420 --> 00:30:21,640
is just about finished.

579
00:30:21,640 --> 00:30:24,090
(cheery music)

580
00:30:27,050 --> 00:30:29,340
Um...

581
00:30:29,340 --> 00:30:30,260
Ahh...

582
00:30:41,730 --> 00:30:45,480
(spine-chilling ominous music)

583
00:30:47,970 --> 00:30:51,570
(distant piano)
(phone rings)

584
00:31:03,710 --> 00:31:06,050
Benderfax Institute...This is Dr. March.

585
00:31:06,460 --> 00:31:09,260
- I'm looking for my wife, Katherine Grider.

586
00:31:09,260 --> 00:31:11,430
- Well I don't recognize the name, sir...

587
00:31:11,430 --> 00:31:13,300
but let me check the admissions records.

588
00:31:13,640 --> 00:31:17,890
[Andrew] Let's see...
Graham, Gray, Griffin, Grant...

589
00:31:18,810 --> 00:31:21,270
I'm sorry, I can't seem to
find her name in the records...

590
00:31:21,270 --> 00:31:24,020
Perhaps she was admitted
to County Hospital.

591
00:31:24,020 --> 00:31:26,070
- They don't know crap.

592
00:31:26,070 --> 00:31:28,860
They told me to call
the Benderfax Institute.

593
00:31:28,860 --> 00:31:30,700
- Well, maybe you could stop by tomorrow...

594
00:31:30,700 --> 00:31:32,340
and talk to Nurse Clench...

595
00:31:32,340 --> 00:31:34,240
If your wife is here...
then she would know for sure.

596
00:31:34,240 --> 00:31:35,730
- Well how would I do that?

597
00:31:35,730 --> 00:31:37,200
I can't walk worth a damn...

598
00:31:37,200 --> 00:31:39,870
I can't do much of anything
without Katherine's help...

599
00:31:39,870 --> 00:31:41,210
Help me out, Doc...

600
00:31:41,210 --> 00:31:43,820
I'm gonna die here in this
God damned apartment...

601
00:31:43,820 --> 00:31:46,840
I can't get around to even
get anything to eat...Nothing...

602
00:31:47,090 --> 00:31:49,670
The damn police won't even take a report...

603
00:31:49,670 --> 00:31:49,690
Nobody does crap!
The damn police won't even take a report...

604
00:31:49,690 --> 00:31:51,430
Nobody does crap!

605
00:31:52,550 --> 00:31:54,430
- Where do you live, Mr. Grider?

606
00:31:54,430 --> 00:31:57,390
- Riviera Hotel...Room 112.

607
00:31:57,850 --> 00:32:00,770
- Okay, I'll tell you what...
that's not too far from here...

608
00:32:00,770 --> 00:32:03,210
Uh...I'll bring you
something to eat tonight...

609
00:32:03,210 --> 00:32:05,690
and we'll see about
getting you help tomorrow.

610
00:32:05,690 --> 00:32:07,360
- Bring me some cigarettes, Doc...

611
00:32:07,360 --> 00:32:08,730
Delta 100's?

612
00:32:12,570 --> 00:32:15,120
- Sure, all right, Mr. Grider.

613
00:32:18,700 --> 00:32:24,030
(mysterious music)

614
00:32:43,940 --> 00:32:45,040
- [Vincent] Who is it?

615
00:32:45,040 --> 00:32:47,960
- Uh...Mr. Grider, it's Andrew March.

616
00:32:47,960 --> 00:32:50,160
- [Vincent] Ah...Come in, Doc.

617
00:32:55,450 --> 00:32:56,430
- Hello...

618
00:32:57,160 --> 00:32:58,690
I got you something to eat.

619
00:32:58,690 --> 00:33:00,250
- Ah...You bring cigarettes?

620
00:33:00,910 --> 00:33:02,910
- Oh, yeah...Delta 100's, right?

621
00:33:02,910 --> 00:33:04,620
- Well, Give 'em here, quick!

622
00:33:06,580 --> 00:33:09,550
[Vincent] Give me a light, Doc...
Matches there on the table.

623
00:33:09,560 --> 00:33:11,550
- Uh...sure.

624
00:33:25,200 --> 00:33:28,940
- You don't know how long it's been
since I've had a smoke, Doc...

625
00:33:28,940 --> 00:33:31,530
I thought I was gonna die...
I really did.

626
00:33:31,530 --> 00:33:32,610
- Listen...

627
00:33:32,610 --> 00:33:35,990
I could arrange for you to get a room
over at the Institute, until--

628
00:33:35,990 --> 00:33:38,030
- I'm not goin' to no hospital...

629
00:33:38,260 --> 00:33:40,170
Just find Katherine, that's all.

630
00:33:40,170 --> 00:33:41,290
- Uh...

631
00:33:42,580 --> 00:33:46,870
Do you...uh...have any pictures
of Katherine, I could look at?

632
00:33:47,330 --> 00:33:48,630
- Pictures?

633
00:33:48,630 --> 00:33:51,590
Uh...Yeah, there's a family album...

634
00:33:51,590 --> 00:33:53,960
right there on the table beside you...

635
00:33:55,300 --> 00:33:56,760
Here, let me have it.

636
00:33:59,510 --> 00:34:00,220
There...

637
00:34:00,220 --> 00:34:01,390
That's Katherine...

638
00:34:01,390 --> 00:34:02,810
14 years old...

639
00:34:02,810 --> 00:34:04,350
Oh, she hates that picture...

640
00:34:04,350 --> 00:34:06,520
That was the year
the dog bit her in the ear...

641
00:34:06,520 --> 00:34:08,600
Swolled up somethin' terrible...

642
00:34:08,730 --> 00:34:10,980
Uh...That's our wedding picture...

643
00:34:10,980 --> 00:34:13,900
And there we are on our
honeymoon...Niagara Falls.

644
00:34:13,900 --> 00:34:15,740
- Uh..No...What I meant is...

645
00:34:15,740 --> 00:34:18,470
do you have anything taken
within the last year or two?

646
00:34:18,470 --> 00:34:22,280
- Oh no...The camera broke
a long time ago...

647
00:34:22,280 --> 00:34:24,200
Don't even know what happened to it...

648
00:34:24,200 --> 00:34:25,700
Wait a minute...Here's somethin'...

649
00:34:25,700 --> 00:34:29,710
This is 1954...That's Katherine
in her bee keepin' outfit...

650
00:34:29,710 --> 00:34:32,500
We had that little bee farm
up by Ramona...

651
00:34:32,500 --> 00:34:34,500
She never got stung neither.

652
00:34:34,500 --> 00:34:39,970
- Did Katherine have an ID card
or a drivers license or--

653
00:34:39,970 --> 00:34:43,260
- No...The state took her drivers
license away a long time ago...

654
00:34:43,260 --> 00:34:44,610
on account of her vision...

655
00:34:44,610 --> 00:34:46,850
She can't see worth a damn.

656
00:34:47,390 --> 00:34:48,730
- Look...

657
00:34:48,730 --> 00:34:52,230
Maybe I can take some of these
pictures back with me, and...

658
00:34:52,230 --> 00:34:54,070
I'll see what I can find out.

659
00:34:55,610 --> 00:34:58,150
- Well, all right...but...

660
00:34:58,150 --> 00:34:59,980
don't let anything happen to 'em...

661
00:34:59,990 --> 00:35:03,910
Katherine'd kill me.

662
00:35:04,490 --> 00:35:12,170
(melancholy piano music)

663
00:35:12,170 --> 00:35:15,710
(laboratory machinery quietly beeps)

664
00:35:17,800 --> 00:35:19,920
- No need to worry, my dear...

665
00:35:19,920 --> 00:35:19,930
You're in good hands...
- No need to worry, my dear...

666
00:35:19,930 --> 00:35:22,550
You're in good hands...

667
00:35:22,550 --> 00:35:27,310
I'll tell you a little story, while we're
waiting for the anesthetic to work...Okay?

668
00:35:27,310 --> 00:35:29,690
It's about my dog, Boxy...

669
00:35:30,270 --> 00:35:32,440
It was many years ago...

670
00:35:32,440 --> 00:35:35,980
but I can still remember just how he looked...

671
00:35:35,980 --> 00:35:40,820
hiding in that cardboard box
in my Father's laboratory...

672
00:35:40,820 --> 00:35:43,620
Boxy loved me right from the start...

673
00:35:43,620 --> 00:35:46,200
and I him...

674
00:35:46,200 --> 00:35:47,950
My course was clear...

675
00:35:47,950 --> 00:35:52,360
I rescued him from the lab
and made him my secret pet...

676
00:35:52,360 --> 00:35:56,380
For more than a month
I kept him hidden in my room...

677
00:35:56,380 --> 00:35:58,760
and for that brief period...

678
00:35:58,760 --> 00:36:02,380
I was truly happy...

679
00:36:02,380 --> 00:36:04,890
But then my father discovered him...

680
00:36:05,390 --> 00:36:09,770
Father didn't care that Boxy was
my best friend in the world...

681
00:36:10,180 --> 00:36:13,690
To Father...little Boxy...

682
00:36:13,690 --> 00:36:16,400
was just a lab dog...

683
00:36:16,420 --> 00:36:19,480
He took him back into his laboratory...

684
00:36:19,970 --> 00:36:23,700
and I never saw him again...

685
00:36:24,490 --> 00:36:25,870
Silly...

686
00:36:25,870 --> 00:36:29,040
but I still think about Boxy sometimes...

687
00:36:29,410 --> 00:36:33,080
The most loyal friend I ever had...

688
00:36:34,580 --> 00:36:37,040
You really are an excellent patient...

689
00:36:37,040 --> 00:36:40,920
Do you know that my dear?

690
00:36:40,920 --> 00:36:43,720
(cheerful music)

691
00:36:44,300 --> 00:36:46,970
- Industrious little guys...aren't they?

692
00:36:46,970 --> 00:36:49,430
- Yeah...I could watch 'em for hours...

693
00:36:49,430 --> 00:36:52,430
They always know exactly what
they're supposed to be doing...

694
00:36:52,430 --> 00:36:54,700
They're always working
for the same purpose...

695
00:36:54,700 --> 00:36:57,360
to make their little world
a little bit better...

696
00:36:58,320 --> 00:37:01,400
People could learn a lot from ants.

697
00:37:01,400 --> 00:37:03,610
- Mm...I agree.

698
00:37:04,200 --> 00:37:05,700
- By the way, Andrew...

699
00:37:05,700 --> 00:37:08,990
thanks for the flowers...They're beautiful.

700
00:37:08,990 --> 00:37:11,540
- I'm glad you like them.

701
00:37:11,540 --> 00:37:14,410
I'm sorry it took me
so long to get here...I...

702
00:37:14,410 --> 00:37:18,210
I went to see a man who called
the...uh...Institute about his wife.

703
00:37:18,210 --> 00:37:19,590
- Oh, really?

704
00:37:19,590 --> 00:37:22,130
- His name's Vincent Grider...

705
00:37:22,130 --> 00:37:24,340
He says his, uh...

706
00:37:24,340 --> 00:37:27,260
he says his wife is...uh...

707
00:37:27,260 --> 00:37:28,890
She's been missing for a few days and so--

708
00:37:28,890 --> 00:37:29,760
- Oh no.

709
00:37:29,760 --> 00:37:31,890
- He's all alone in his apartment, so I just...

710
00:37:31,890 --> 00:37:35,640
I brought some food
and cigarettes over...to him.

711
00:37:35,640 --> 00:37:38,360
- Oh, that's so sweet of you.

712
00:37:38,360 --> 00:37:41,110
- Oh, it was...it was no big deal.

713
00:37:41,110 --> 00:37:43,320
- You're so modest.

714
00:37:51,080 --> 00:37:54,120
(suspenseful music)

715
00:37:59,540 --> 00:38:04,170
- Test subject K26...white female...late 60's...

716
00:38:04,170 --> 00:38:06,340
possible stroke victim...

717
00:38:06,340 --> 00:38:10,220
Image acceleration threshold was
much lower than previous subjects...

718
00:38:10,220 --> 00:38:15,430
apparently due to a high adrenal output...
enhancing the electrochemical field...

719
00:38:15,430 --> 00:38:19,770
This increase in field potential
seems inversely related to the...

720
00:38:19,770 --> 00:38:21,480
sensor distance...

721
00:38:21,480 --> 00:38:25,400
Therefore, placing the sensor
probes directly in contact...

722
00:38:25,400 --> 00:38:27,400
with the adrenal cortex...

723
00:38:27,400 --> 00:38:30,030
may resolve the interference problems...

724
00:38:30,030 --> 00:38:30,740
(knocking)

725
00:38:30,740 --> 00:38:31,930
Come in.

726
00:38:33,620 --> 00:38:35,120
Oh, it's you, Andrew...

727
00:38:36,910 --> 00:38:38,860
How are my illustrations coming along?

728
00:38:38,860 --> 00:38:41,170
- Oh, just fine Sir.

729
00:38:41,170 --> 00:38:42,920
- Glad to hear it...

730
00:38:42,920 --> 00:38:44,340
Cookie?

731
00:38:44,340 --> 00:38:45,370
- Thank you, Sir.

732
00:38:46,890 --> 00:38:48,260
- [Benderfax] What can I do for you?

733
00:38:48,260 --> 00:38:49,890
- Mm...actually...

734
00:38:49,890 --> 00:38:53,760
I've gotten myself into
an awkward situation...

735
00:38:53,760 --> 00:38:55,480
and I wanted your advice.

736
00:38:55,480 --> 00:38:57,000
- What's the problem?

737
00:38:57,000 --> 00:38:59,900
- A man called the Institute last night...
looking for his wife...

738
00:38:59,900 --> 00:39:03,270
Apparently, County Hospital had
told him that she was here.

739
00:39:03,270 --> 00:39:04,820
- The woman's name?

740
00:39:04,820 --> 00:39:06,780
- [Andrew] Katherine Grider, Sir.

741
00:39:07,150 --> 00:39:08,530
- Grider?

742
00:39:09,070 --> 00:39:10,370
Not one of ours.

743
00:39:10,370 --> 00:39:12,130
- Yes Sir, I know...

744
00:39:12,130 --> 00:39:13,450
but Mr. Grider...

745
00:39:13,450 --> 00:39:15,570
sounded pretty bad on the phone...

746
00:39:15,570 --> 00:39:18,250
He said he hadn't eaten
since his wife left...

747
00:39:18,250 --> 00:39:19,790
So, I went to see him.

748
00:39:19,790 --> 00:39:20,540
- Oh?

749
00:39:20,540 --> 00:39:22,290
- Yeah, he lives just a few blocks away...

750
00:39:22,290 --> 00:39:24,000
at the Riviera Hotel...

751
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:24,020
Um...well...
at the Riviera Hotel...

752
00:39:24,020 --> 00:39:25,880
Um...well...

753
00:39:25,880 --> 00:39:27,710
I just by to check up on him...

754
00:39:27,710 --> 00:39:30,050
and while I was there...

755
00:39:30,050 --> 00:39:33,140
I told him I'd help him find his wife...

756
00:39:33,890 --> 00:39:36,220
He gave me these photos of her...

757
00:39:38,170 --> 00:39:39,480
I called the police about this...

758
00:39:39,480 --> 00:39:42,850
but they have no report
of a woman matching her description...

759
00:39:42,850 --> 00:39:45,880
I was hoping perhaps you'd
have some idea of what to do.

760
00:39:48,150 --> 00:39:49,740
- These aren't recent, I take it?

761
00:39:50,030 --> 00:39:51,320
- No...

762
00:39:51,320 --> 00:39:55,280
Mrs. Grider is somewhere
in her mid 60's by now...

763
00:39:55,280 --> 00:39:56,870
Not much to go on, are they?

764
00:39:57,160 --> 00:39:59,250
- Hm...no...

765
00:39:59,250 --> 00:40:00,870
I'll make a few calls...

766
00:40:00,870 --> 00:40:02,500
and see what I can find out.

767
00:40:02,500 --> 00:40:04,580
- Well, thank you Sir...
I would appreciate it.

768
00:40:04,580 --> 00:40:06,460
- Consider it done, Andrew...

769
00:40:06,460 --> 00:40:07,650
Is there anything else?

770
00:40:08,090 --> 00:40:09,760
- [Andrew] Yes, actually...

771
00:40:09,760 --> 00:40:12,340
I wanted to talk to you
to you about Wilma Beagle...

772
00:40:12,340 --> 00:40:13,970
the new stroke patient...

773
00:40:13,990 --> 00:40:15,600
She's been moved from her room...

774
00:40:15,600 --> 00:40:17,510
and no one seems to know where she is.

775
00:40:17,510 --> 00:40:19,020
- [Benderfax] You haven't heard?

776
00:40:19,020 --> 00:40:20,430
- Heard what, Sir?

777
00:40:20,430 --> 00:40:22,810
- Cerebral aneurism, I'm afraid...

778
00:40:22,810 --> 00:40:24,100
late last night...

779
00:40:24,100 --> 00:40:26,020
It was all very sudden.

780
00:40:27,480 --> 00:40:29,400
- But...but I was working with her...

781
00:40:29,400 --> 00:40:31,110
just yesterday.

782
00:40:31,110 --> 00:40:33,110
- Yes, poor woman...

783
00:40:33,110 --> 00:40:36,160
Sadly, these things
are quite hard to predict.

784
00:40:38,720 --> 00:40:40,580
- I see.

785
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:45,670
(melancholy piano music)

786
00:41:31,730 --> 00:41:36,730
(dramatic upbeat music)

787
00:41:43,810 --> 00:41:45,690
(music fades)

